In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command generates the table of contents based on the sections and subsections in the document. The `\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Custom Entry}` command adds a custom entry named "Custom Entry" to the table of contents. The `\label{customentry}` command creates a reference that can be used to link to this custom entry using the `\autoref{customentry}` command.</s>

To draw a chessboard in LATEX, you can use the `chessboard` package. Here's a simple example of how to create a FEN board using this package.

First, make sure you have the `chessboard` package installed. If not, add it to your document preamble:

```latex
\usepackage{chessboard}
```

Next, create a command to draw the board, which I'll call `\drawFENBoard`. This command takes one argument: the FEN (Forsyth-Edwards Notation) string.

```latex
\newcommand{\drawFENBoard}[1]{
    \begin{center}
        \begin{chessboard}[
            setfen={#1},
            size=6em,
            color=black,
            markings=empty
        ]
        \end{chessboard}
    \end{center}
}
```

Now you can draw a board using your FEN string like this:

```latex
\drawFENBoard{8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8}
```

This will draw a standard empty board. To draw a FEN board, replace `8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8` with the FEN string. Here's an example with a simple FEN string:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\newcommand{\drawFENBoard}[1]{
    \begin{center}
        \begin{chessboard}[
            setfen={#1},
            size=6em,
            color=black,
            markings=empty
        ]
        \end{chessboard}
    \end{center}
}
\begin{document}
\drawFENBoard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}
\end{document}
```

This code will generate a board with the starting position of a chess game:

```
  ♜ ♞        p   p
  ♝ ♘        p   p
  ♛ ♔        p   p
  ♜ ♞        p   p
  ♝ ♘        p   p
  ♛ ♔        p   p
  ♚ ♛        p   p
  ♔ ♚        p   p
```

You can adjust the size variable in the `chessboard` command to change the size of the board. The color argument can be adjusted to change the color of the squares (black or white). The markings argument can be changed to show piece positions in addition to the board itself. For more details on the `chessboard` package, consult its documentation: http://mirrors.ctan.org/macros/latex/contrib/chessboard/chessboard.pdf.</s>

